@yugusmedugus4005¬† I'm of course talking about my own individual context in England, where a cows diet is 70% grass.

But the general rule applies. It cannot be assumed that you could just take what the animal eats and eat it yourself, that presumes a diet of human grade food for the animal; which isn't true. One also has to factor that livestock also support crops, a great deal of organic plant fertilisers are derived from manures.

The narrative that you could just get rid of animals and suddenly you are a more sustainable and environmentally friendly diet is a fiction. The people in India also have distended bellies as a result of all the plant matter fermentation in their gut, there are tradeoffs.

Bookmarked for future me due to the message at the end;

I went through most of my life feeling like a failure as I struggled to do what everyone else seemed to manage as "normal", until I really burnt out hard and it dawned on me I might be disabled. So I got diagnosed and was able to claim disability benefits and for the past few years I have finally been allowed to feel somewhat human with a sense of stability and not just pure and constent existential dread (like, for most people I saw online, covid lockdowns were really hard times, but for me it was the first time I felt I could breathe since childhood).

And just as I am settling into the idea that I might actually want to keep living, now that I don't have to force myself to play the same game of charades as everyone else; my government (UK, who we just voted in as the so called opposition to the right wing party, what a fucking joke...) are threatening to take away this critical safety net for the most vulnerable, and I may once again fall through the cracks of a broken system and I don't know if I would be able to come back from a place like that again...

