You assume people's circumstances, that it's practical for them to buy in bulk, that they have a hand mixer and a large freezer and a car to carry bulk groceries, the ability to consume bulk groceries before they go off, space to store bulk groceries. Your suggestion is to walk back and forth to the store hauling 15kg sacks of potatos and onions and then stack them up on the floor of my one room apartment, then prepare 20 portions of jambalaya and learn cannery to preserve them. And you better not screw up one of these recipes you found online and are trying for the first time or else you just blew the food budget for the wee. All to save like $60 a month, and then saying it's easy. But if you're actually hurting for money, you can save even more by eating ramen or other already edible foods that don't require any additional ingredients or preparation, or probably make even more by working a couple hours extra a week instead.

I just think cooking isn't the panacea to poverty influencers claim it is, because everyone has a different circumstance. And just like there are cheap and expensive ways too cook, there are also cheap and expensive ways to buy food without cooking.

